<br>
Sweetie, I know completely what you are going through. My grandmother passed not too long ago from cancer, as well. I didn't visit her much when she was well, and when she got sick, I was just too scared to visit her. I didn't want to face the fact that my grandmother that I loved so much was dying. Then, she passed, and I was kicking myself in the ass for not showing her how much I loved her and taking her for granted for 22 years.<br>
<br>
My Mother told me that my grandmother new how much I loved her, and I accept that, because I really have no choice. The only thing I can do now is make sure to make my time count with the family I have left, and that is the only advice that I can offer you. Besides that, I have my cyber ears and shoulder, which are always here if you need to talk.<br>
<br>
Have a safe trip and know that you and your grandmother will be in my thoughts. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=kuladen>kuladen</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>FV's Mr. Mackey<br>Greatest<br>Sexiest<be>Bard<br>Ever.</span><br>  Posts: 1837<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(6/9/03 6:41 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1648.topic&index=5>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.inkbard.com/art/kuladenclrthmb.jpg  WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Well, there's a first time for everything</span><hr size=1> I know what you are going through. While it was not the first death in my family (I remember getting out of junior high in 1991 for my great grandfather's funeral), it was the first that I was real close to.<br>
<br>
My grandfather died Nov 19, 1999. My name is Douglass William Beekman, II. His was Douglass William Beekman. He was in the hospital for fainting, and they had given him a clean bill of health. That morning he called my grandmother, telling her that he was ready to come home, and to come pick her up.<br>
<br>
He died with the phone still in his hand. He said 'ok, I love you, see you soon'. She hung up. <br>
<br>
He didn't.<br>
<br>
It was quite the shock to all of us. My brother had to drive to my house an hour away and drive me back. <br>
<br>
I had to sit through a funeral listening to my name being eulogized. My grandmother went a little mad. <br>
<br>
It was a very bad time, because noone was expecting it. I didn't bother to go see him in the hospital, because it wasn't that big of deal. We didn't know. Noone knew.<br>
<br>
But I take solace in the fact that even though noone got to say goodbye, he knew. And while I'm not aware of what lies beyond, I know that he knew of my love for him, and I know he loved me. <br>
<br>
My grandmother read a poem while we were planting a tree for him. <br>
<br>
